@DEberhardt the AzureAD team is a black box, they haven't made any announcements of any kind regarding that as far as I'm aware.

Currently the only supported path is the Microsoft Graph Powershell SDK. Microsoft Graph covers about 90% of what the deprecated AzureAD Graph API covered. These commands are not as "friendly" as AzureAD though, hence the SDK label. A new AzureAD module could theoretically be built using the SDK as a base, but again, nothing's been announced that I'm aware of.

There are also some AD commands in Az.Resources which, while using the deprecated AzureAD API, do work with PS7. It's not a full coverage but is good enough for some use cases.

@arendkolk AzureAD is not a supported module outside of Windows currently, period. You can get the AzureAD.Standard.Preview module which does work on linux but that is unsupported outside of cloudshell.

You should be using the Microsoft Graph Powershell SDK for Azure AD operations in Powershell 7. A subset of functionality is also availabile in the Az.Resources module however that still uses the legacy AzAD graph api rather than Microsoft Graph.

There is no roadmap for AzureAD moving to Powershell 7 (yet, the VP for the team has promised a blog article roadmap)
